>>  It's anyone working on this ?? ... I have this chipset on my notebook and
>> I want to use the multimedia extension it has, such as the PAL/NTSC video
>> input/output features ...
>
>You want to talk to XFree86 rather than the kernel folks for that one.
 Maybe I had not explain myselft ...
 I *DON'T* need a X server .. the SVGA server works ok for this chipset
...
 What I want it's a v4l driver like the bttv but without tunning features
(the chipset don't have a turner).
 Here you have a summary of the chipset features ... (from Intel's specs)
 65555 (HiQVPro [tm]) High Performance Multimedia Flat Panel/CRT GUI Accelerator
 -PC 97 Compilant
 -Highly integrated desing Flat panel and CRT GUI Accelerator & Multimedia
Engine, Palette/DAC, and Clock Synthesizer
 -Hardware Windows Acceleration
	64-bit Graphics Engine
	  System-To-Screen and
          Screen-To-Screen BitBLT
	  3-Operand Rester-Ops
	  6/16/24 Color Expansion
	Transparent BLT
	  Optimized for Windows BitBLT format
 -PCI Bus with Brust Mode capability and BIOS ROM Support
 -Flexible Memory Configurations 
  [...cutted...]
 -Hardware Multimedia Support
	Zoom Video port  (ZV PCMCIA Port)
	YUV input from System Bus or Video Port
	YUV-RGB Conversion
	Capture/Scaling
	Video Zoom up to 8x
	Vertical interpolation of video data up to 720 pixels wide
	Double Buffered Video
	Horizontal Interpolation
 [...cutted...]
 -Game Acceleration
	Source Transparent BLT
	Destination Transparent BLT
	Double Buffer support for YUV and 15/16bpp Overlay Engine
	Instant Full Screen Page Flip
	Read Back of CRT Scan line counters
 I have my X server running OK, what I really want it's to be able to use
the capture/playing features, to be able to use videoconferencing software
and that's part of v4l I think ... :-?
